Prove by induction that for all non-negative integers [latex]n[/latex], the number [latex]n^3 + 2 n[/latex] is divisible by 3.

&nbsp;

Recall that integer [latex]a[/latex] is divisible by [latex]d[/latex] if there exists an integer [latex]m[/latex] such that [latex]a = md[/latex].

What is wrong with Polya&#039;s classic proof that all horses are the same color?

I&#039;d suggest rewriting this to follow my template and see if that clarifies what goes wrong.

&nbsp;

CLAIM: In any set of [latex]h[/latex] horses, all horses are the same color.

&nbsp;

<em>FaultyProof</em> by Induction on [latex]h[/latex].

&nbsp;

Base: For [latex]h = 1[/latex]. In any set containing just one horse, all horses clearly are the same color.

&nbsp;

Induction Step: For [latex]kge 1[/latex] assume that the claim is true for [latex]h = k[/latex] and prove that it is true for [latex]h = k+1[/latex].

&nbsp;

Take any set [latex]H[/latex] of [latex]k+1[/latex] horses. We show that all the horses in this set are the same color. Remove one horse from this set to obtain the set [latex]H _ 1[/latex] with just [latex]k[/latex] horses. By the induction hypothesis, all the horses in [latex]H _ 1[/latex] are the same color. Now replace the removed horse and remove a different one to obtain the set [latex]H _ 2[/latex]. By the same argument, all the horses in [latex]H _ 2[/latex] are the same color. Therefore, all the horses in [latex]H[/latex] must be the same color, and the proof is complete.

