What is wrong with this induction proof that [latex]a^n=1[/latex] always?

&nbsp;

Claim: Let [latex]a[/latex] be any positive number. For all positive integers [latex]n[/latex], we have a

[latex]a^{n-1} = 1[/latex].

&nbsp;

<em>FaultyProof</em> by induction on [latex]n[/latex]

&nbsp;

Basis: If [latex]n = 1[/latex], we have [latex]a^{n-1}= 1[/latex]. [latex]checkmark[/latex]

&nbsp;

Inductive Step: We want to prove this for an integer [latex]n&gt;1[/latex].

&nbsp;

Inductive Hypothesis: Assume, for all natural numbers [latex]k&lt;n[/latex], that [latex]a^{k-1}= 1[/latex].

&nbsp;

We now want to show that it is true for [latex]n[/latex] by writing

[latex]a^{n-1} = frac{a^{n-2}cdot a^{n-2}}{a^{n-3}}, [/latex]since [latex]n-1 = (n-2)+(n-2) - (n-3)[/latex]. But if we use the inductive hypothesis twice, for [latex]k=n-1[/latex] and [latex]k=n-2[/latex], we can replace [latex]a^{n-2}=1[/latex] and [latex]a^{n-3}=1[/latex],
so [latex]a^{n-1} = frac{1cdot1}{1} = 1.[/latex]

