Can you show that the number guessing game has a worst case of exactly [latex]lceillog_2 nceil[/latex] guesses?

&nbsp;

I&#039;m thinking of a natural number [latex]x[/latex] between 1 and [latex]n[/latex]. You can ask questions of the form, ``Is [latex]x[/latex] larger than [latex]a[/latex]?&#039;&#039; and I will tell you (truthfully) yes or no. Show that, in the worst case, [latex]lceillog_2 nceil[/latex] questions are necessary and sufficient to exactly determine my number.

&nbsp;

For sufficiency, you may want to argue that you can round [latex]n[/latex] up to the next power of 2 to make your proof easier: e.g., new [latex]n=2^{lceillog_2 nceil}[/latex].

&nbsp;

To show that this many are necessary is harder, you have to imagine that you are the one picking the number, but you keep your options open until the guesser starts asking questions.

Nim is a simple two players game with two stacks of chips, matches, or other counters. At each turn, a player removes some (non-zero) number of counters from one of the stacks. In this variant, the player who removes the last match wins.

&nbsp;

If the two piles contain the same number of matches at the start of the game, show that the second player can always win with the following strategy: always take the same number of matches that your opponent took, but from the other pile.

